data.content:
These are three well-known C# 13 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and the fixes:

## 1. `Buffer.cs` — `[InlineArray]` on record structs is now an error

C# 13 prohibits `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` because the compiler-synthesized `Equals`/`GetHashCode`/`ToString` only inspect `_element0`, silently ignoring the rest of the array. Change to a plain `struct`:

```csharp
[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]
struct Buffer
{
    private int _element0;
}
```

## 2. `Generator.cs` — `unsafe` on the class now flows into iterators

In C# 12, `unsafe` on a type did **not** propagate into iterator methods. C# 13 changed this — the iterator is now in an unsafe context, and `stackalloc` is illegal inside iterators (even in local functions). Remove `unsafe` from the class and apply it directly to the local function:

```csharp
class DataGenerator
{
    IEnumerable<int> Generate()
    {
        yield return 1;
        Process();
        unsafe void Process()
        {
            int* p = stackalloc int[10];
            // ... work with pointer
        }
    }
}
```

## 3. `Resolver.cs` — New implicit span conversions cause ambiguity

C# 13 adds first-class implicit conversions between `Span<T>`, `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and arrays. The empty collection expression `[]` is now **ambiguous** between the two `Process` overloads because neither conversion is "better" under the new rules. Fix by specifying the target type explicitly:

```csharp
static void Main()
{
    Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);
}
```
